  <COMMENT line1="1" col1="1" line2="1" col2="76" start="331" end="406">## Convenience function for computing QC metrics and adding to pData &amp; fData</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2" col1="1" line2="2" col2="63" start="661" end="723">### This file contains definitions for the following functions:</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="3" col1="1" line2="3" col2="24" start="991" end="1014">### * calculateQCMetrics</COMMENT>

  <COMMENT line1="6" col1="1" line2="6" col2="22" start="1981" end="2002">### * plotHighestExprs</COMMENT>

  <COMMENT line1="9" col1="1" line2="9" col2="31" start="2971" end="3001">### * .calculateSilhouetteWidth</COMMENT>

  <COMMENT line1="15" col1="1" line2="15" col2="23" start="4951" end="4973">#' Calculate QC metrics</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="16" col1="1" line2="16" col2="2" start="5281" end="5282">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="17" col1="1" line2="17" col2="66" start="5611" end="5676">#' @param object an SCESet object containing expression values and</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="18" col1="1" line2="18" col2="67" start="5941" end="6007">#' experimental information. Must have been appropriately prepared.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="19" col1="1" line2="19" col2="71" start="6271" end="6341">#' @param feature_controls a named list containing one or more vectors </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="20" col1="1" line2="20" col2="77" start="6601" end="6677">#' (character vector of feature names, logical vector, or a numeric vector of</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="21" col1="1" line2="21" col2="65" start="6931" end="6995">#' indices are all acceptable) used to identify feature controls </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="22" col1="1" line2="22" col2="65" start="7261" end="7325">#' (for example, ERCC spike-in genes, mitochondrial genes, etc). </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="23" col1="1" line2="23" col2="79" start="7591" end="7669">#' @param cell_controls a character vector of cell (sample) names, or a logical</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="24" col1="1" line2="24" col2="77" start="7921" end="7997">#' vector, or a numeric vector of indices used to identify cell controls (for</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="25" col1="1" line2="25" col2="42" start="8251" end="8292">#' example, blank wells or bulk controls).</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="26" col1="1" line2="26" col2="79" start="8581" end="8659">#' @param nmads numeric scalar giving the number of median absolute deviations </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="27" col1="1" line2="27" col2="80" start="8911" end="8990">#' to be used to flag potentially problematic cells based on total_counts (total</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="28" col1="1" line2="28" col2="80" start="9241" end="9320">#' number of counts for the cell, or library size) and total_features (number of</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="29" col1="1" line2="29" col2="80" start="9571" end="9650">#' features with non-zero expression). For total_features, cells are flagged for</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="30" col1="1" line2="30" col2="78" start="9901" end="9978">#' filtering only if total_features is \code{nmads} below the median. Default </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="31" col1="1" line2="31" col2="14" start="10231" end="10244">#' value is 5.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="32" col1="1" line2="32" col2="78" start="10561" end="10638">#' @param pct_feature_controls_threshold numeric scalar giving a threshold for</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="33" col1="1" line2="33" col2="80" start="10891" end="10970">#' percentage of expression values accounted for by feature controls. Used as to</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="34" col1="1" line2="34" col2="78" start="11221" end="11298">#' flag cells that may be filtered based on high percentage of expression from</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="35" col1="1" line2="35" col2="20" start="11551" end="11570">#' feature controls.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="36" col1="1" line2="36" col2="2" start="11881" end="11882">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="37" col1="1" line2="37" col2="80" start="12211" end="12290">#' @details Calculate useful quality control metrics to help with pre-processing</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="38" col1="1" line2="38" col2="77" start="12541" end="12617">#' of data and identification of potentially problematic features and cells. </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="39" col1="1" line2="39" col2="3" start="12871" end="12873">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="40" col1="1" line2="40" col2="41" start="13201" end="13241">#' The following QC metrics are computed:</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="41" col1="1" line2="41" col2="13" start="13531" end="13543">#' \describe{</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="42" col1="1" line2="42" col2="76" start="13861" end="13936">#'  \item{total_counts:}{Total number of counts for the cell (aka ``library </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="43" col1="1" line2="43" col2="12" start="14191" end="14202">#'  size'')}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="44" col1="1" line2="44" col2="63" start="14521" end="14583">#'  \item{log10_total_counts:}{Total counts on the log10-scale}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="45" col1="1" line2="45" col2="78" start="14851" end="14928">#'  \item{total_features:}{The number of endogenous features (i.e. not control</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="46" col1="1" line2="46" col2="73" start="15181" end="15253">#'  features) for the cell that have expression above the detection limit</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="47" col1="1" line2="47" col2="39" start="15511" end="15549">#'   (default detection limit is zero)}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="48" col1="1" line2="48" col2="72" start="15841" end="15912">#'  \item{filter_on_depth:}{Would this cell be filtered out based on its</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="49" col1="1" line2="49" col2="78" start="16171" end="16248">#'  log10-depth being (by default) more than 5 median absolute deviations from</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="50" col1="1" line2="50" col2="44" start="16501" end="16544">#'  the median log10-depth for the dataset?}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="51" col1="1" line2="51" col2="75" start="16831" end="16905">#'  \item{filter_on_coverage:}{Would this cell be filtered out based on its</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="52" col1="1" line2="52" col2="79" start="17161" end="17239">#'  coverage being (by default) more than 5 median absolute deviations from the</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="53" col1="1" line2="53" col2="37" start="17491" end="17527">#'  median coverage for the dataset?}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="54" col1="1" line2="54" col2="77" start="17821" end="17897">#'  \item{filter_on_pct_counts_feature_controls:}{Should the cell be filtered</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="55" col1="1" line2="55" col2="78" start="18151" end="18228">#'  out on the basis of having a high percentage of counts assigned to control</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="56" col1="1" line2="56" col2="75" start="18481" end="18555">#'  features? Default threshold is 80 percent (i.e. cells with more than 80</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="57" col1="1" line2="57" col2="65" start="18811" end="18875">#'  percent of counts assigned to feature controls are flagged).}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="58" col1="1" line2="58" col2="71" start="19141" end="19211">#'  \item{counts_feature_controls:}{Total number of counts for the cell</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="59" col1="1" line2="59" col2="80" start="19471" end="19550">#'  that come from (one or more sets of user-defined) control features. Defaults</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="60" col1="1" line2="60" col2="74" start="19801" end="19874">#'   to zero if no control features are indicated. If more than one set of</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="61" col1="1" line2="61" col2="77" start="20131" end="20207">#'   feature controls are defined (for example, ERCC and MT genes are defined</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="62" col1="1" line2="62" col2="79" start="20461" end="20539">#'   as controls), then this metric is produced for all sets, plus the union of</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="63" col1="1" line2="63" col2="38" start="20791" end="20828">#'   all sets (so here, we get columns</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="64" col1="1" line2="64" col2="41" start="21121" end="21161">#'   \code{counts_feature_controls_ERCC},</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="65" col1="1" line2="65" col2="42" start="21451" end="21492">#'   \code{counts_feature_controls_MT} and</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="66" col1="1" line2="66" col2="38" start="21781" end="21818">#'   \code{counts_feature_controls}).}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="67" col1="1" line2="67" col2="66" start="22111" end="22176">#'  \item{log10_counts_feature_controls:}{Just as above, the total</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="68" col1="1" line2="68" col2="77" start="22441" end="22517">#'   number of counts from feature controls, but on the log10-scale. Defaults</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="69" col1="1" line2="69" col2="77" start="22771" end="22847">#'   to zero (i.e.~log10(0 + 1), offset to avoid negative infinite values) if</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="70" col1="1" line2="70" col2="39" start="23101" end="23139">#'   no feature control are indicated.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="71" col1="1" line2="71" col2="62" start="23431" end="23492">#'  \item{pct_counts_feature_controls:}{Just as for the counts</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="72" col1="1" line2="72" col2="72" start="23761" end="23832">#'   described above, but expressed as a percentage of the total counts.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="73" col1="1" line2="73" col2="76" start="24091" end="24166">#'   Defined for all control sets and their union, just like the raw counts.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="74" col1="1" line2="74" col2="58" start="24421" end="24478">#'   Defaults to zero if no feature controls are defined.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="75" col1="1" line2="75" col2="68" start="24751" end="24818">#'  \item{filter_on_pct_counts_feature_controls:}{Would this cell be</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="76" col1="1" line2="76" col2="73" start="25081" end="25153">#'   filtered out on the basis that the percentage of counts from feature</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="77" col1="1" line2="77" col2="79" start="25411" end="25489">#'   controls is higher than a defined threhold (default is 80\%)? Just as with</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="78" col1="1" line2="78" col2="73" start="25741" end="25813">#'   \code{counts_feature_controls}, this is defined for all control sets</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="79" col1="1" line2="79" col2="22" start="26071" end="26092">#'   and their union.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="80" col1="1" line2="80" col2="329" start="26401" end="26729">#'  \item{pct_counts_top_50_features:}{What percentage of the total counts is accounted for by the 50 highest-count features? Also computed for the top 100 and top 200 features, with the obvious changes to the column names. Note that the top ``X'' percentage will not be computed if the total number of genes is less than ``X''.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="81" col1="1" line2="81" col2="73" start="26731" end="26803">#'  \item{pct_dropout:}{Percentage of features that are not ``detectably </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="82" col1="1" line2="82" col2="75" start="27061" end="27135">#'  expressed'', i.e. have expression below the \code{lowerDetectionLimit} </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="83" col1="1" line2="83" col2="15" start="27391" end="27405">#'  threshold.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="84" col1="1" line2="84" col2="74" start="27721" end="27794">#'  \item{counts_endogenous_features:}{Total number of counts for the cell</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="85" col1="1" line2="85" col2="77" start="28051" end="28127">#'   that come from endogenous features (i.e. not control features). Defaults</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="86" col1="1" line2="86" col2="54" start="28381" end="28434">#'   to `depth` if no control features are indicated.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="87" col1="1" line2="87" col2="72" start="28711" end="28782">#'  \item{log10_counts_endogenous_features:}{Total number of counts from</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="88" col1="1" line2="88" col2="74" start="29041" end="29114">#'   endogenous features on the log10-scale. Defaults to all counts if no </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="89" col1="1" line2="89" col2="37" start="29371" end="29407">#'   control features are indicated.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="90" col1="1" line2="90" col2="74" start="29701" end="29774">#'  \item{n_detected_feature_controls:}{Number of defined feature controls</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="91" col1="1" line2="91" col2="75" start="30031" end="30105">#'    that have expression greater than the threshold defined in the object</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="92" col1="1" line2="92" col2="54" start="30361" end="30414">#'    (that is, they are ``detectably expressed''; see</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="93" col1="1" line2="93" col2="78" start="30691" end="30768">#'    \code{object@lowerDetectionLimit} to check the threshold). As with other</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="94" col1="1" line2="94" col2="76" start="31021" end="31096">#'    metrics for feature controls, defined for all sets of feature controls</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="95" col1="1" line2="95" col2="77" start="31351" end="31427">#'    (set names appended as above) and their union. So we might commonly get</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="96" col1="1" line2="96" col2="54" start="31681" end="31734">#'    columns \code{n_detected_feature_controls_ERCC},</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="97" col1="1" line2="97" col2="47" start="32011" end="32057">#'    \code{n_detected_feature_controls_MT} and</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="98" col1="1" line2="98" col2="71" start="32341" end="32411">#'    \code{n_detected_feature_controls} (ERCC and MT genes detected).}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="99" col1="1" line2="99" col2="75" start="32671" end="32745">#'  \item{is_cell_control:}{Has the cell been defined as a cell control? If</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="100" col1="1" line2="100" col2="77" start="33001" end="33077">#'    more than one set of cell controls are defined (for example, blanks and</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="101" col1="1" line2="101" col2="80" start="33331" end="33410">#'    bulk libraries are defined as cell controls), then this metric is produced</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="102" col1="1" line2="102" col2="74" start="33661" end="33734">#'     for all sets, plus the union of all sets (so we could typically get</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="103" col1="1" line2="103" col2="44" start="33991" end="34034">#'     columns \code{is_cell_control_Blank},</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="104" col1="1" line2="104" col2="74" start="34321" end="34394">#'     \code{is_cell_control_Bulk}, and \code{is_cell_control}, the latter</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="105" col1="1" line2="105" col2="58" start="34651" end="34708">#'     including both blanks and bulks as cell controls).}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="106" col1="1" line2="106" col2="4" start="34981" end="34984">#' }</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="107" col1="1" line2="107" col2="76" start="35311" end="35386">#' These cell-level QC metrics are added as columns to the ``phenotypeData''</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="108" col1="1" line2="108" col2="73" start="35641" end="35713">#' slot of the \code{SCESet} object so that they can be inspected and are</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="109" col1="1" line2="109" col2="70" start="35971" end="36040">#' readily available for other functions to use. Furthermore, wherever</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="110" col1="1" line2="110" col2="72" start="36301" end="36372">#' ``counts'' appear in the above metrics, the same metrics will also be</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="111" col1="1" line2="111" col2="78" start="36631" end="36708">#' computed for ``exprs'', ``tpm'' and ``fpkm'' values (if TPM and FPKM values</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="112" col1="1" line2="112" col2="70" start="36961" end="37030">#' are present in the \code{SCESet} object), with the appropriate term</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="113" col1="1" line2="113" col2="79" start="37291" end="37369">#' replacing ``counts'' in the name. The following feature-level QC metrics are</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="114" col1="1" line2="114" col2="17" start="37621" end="37637">#' also computed:</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="115" col1="1" line2="115" col2="13" start="37951" end="37963">#' \describe{</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="116" col1="1" line2="116" col2="70" start="38281" end="38350">#' \item{mean_exprs:}{The mean expression level of the  gene/feature.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="117" col1="1" line2="117" col2="76" start="38611" end="38686">#' \item{exprs_rank:}{The rank of the feature's mean expression level in the</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="118" col1="1" line2="118" col2="9" start="38941" end="38949">#' cell.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="119" col1="1" line2="119" col2="78" start="39271" end="39348">#' \item{n_cells_exprs:}{The number of cells for which the expression level of</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="120" col1="1" line2="120" col2="79" start="39601" end="39679">#' the feature is above the detection limit (default detection limit is zero).}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="121" col1="1" line2="121" col2="75" start="39931" end="40005">#' \item{total_feature_counts:}{The total number of counts assigned to that</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="122" col1="1" line2="122" col2="29" start="40261" end="40289">#' feature across all cells.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="123" col1="1" line2="123" col2="79" start="40591" end="40669">#' \item{log10_total_feature_counts:}{Total feature counts on the log10-scale.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="124" col1="1" line2="124" col2="79" start="40921" end="40999">#' \item{pct_total_counts:}{The percentage of all counts that are accounted for</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="125" col1="1" line2="125" col2="42" start="41251" end="41292">#' by the counts assigned to the feature.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="126" col1="1" line2="126" col2="75" start="41581" end="41655">#' \item{pct_dropout:}{The percentage of all cells that have no detectable </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="127" col1="1" line2="127" col2="78" start="41911" end="41988">#' expression (i.e. \code{is_exprs(object)} is \code{FALSE}) for the feature.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="128" col1="1" line2="128" col2="74" start="42241" end="42314">#' \item{is_feature_control:}{Is the feature a control feature? Default is</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="129" col1="1" line2="129" col2="76" start="42571" end="42646">#' `FALSE` unless control features are defined by the user. If more than one</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="130" col1="1" line2="130" col2="75" start="42901" end="42975">#' feature control set is defined (as above), then a column of this type is</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="131" col1="1" line2="131" col2="79" start="43231" end="43309">#' produced for each control set (e.g. here, \code{is_feature_control_ERCC} and</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="132" col1="1" line2="132" col2="60" start="43561" end="43620">#' \code{is_feature_control_MT}) as well as the column named</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="133" col1="1" line2="133" col2="78" start="43891" end="43968">#' \code{is_feature_control}, which indicates if the feature belongs to any of</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="134" col1="1" line2="134" col2="21" start="44221" end="44241">#' the control sets.}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="135" col1="1" line2="135" col2="4" start="44551" end="44554">#' }</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="136" col1="1" line2="136" col2="77" start="44881" end="44957">#' These feature-level QC metrics are added as columns to the ``featureData''</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="137" col1="1" line2="137" col2="73" start="45211" end="45283">#' slot of the \code{SCESet} object so that they can be inspected and are</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="138" col1="1" line2="138" col2="80" start="45541" end="45620">#' readily available for other functions to use. As with the cell-level metrics,</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="139" col1="1" line2="139" col2="74" start="45871" end="45944">#'  wherever ``counts'' appear in the above, the same metrics will also be</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="140" col1="1" line2="140" col2="79" start="46201" end="46279">#'  computed for ``exprs'', ``tpm'' and ``fpkm'' values (if TPM and FPKM values</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="141" col1="1" line2="141" col2="71" start="46531" end="46601">#'  are present in the \code{SCESet} object), with the appropriate term</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="142" col1="1" line2="142" col2="37" start="46861" end="46897">#'  replacing ``counts'' in the name.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="143" col1="1" line2="143" col2="2" start="47191" end="47192">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="144" col1="1" line2="144" col2="27" start="47521" end="47547">#' @return an SCESet object</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="145" col1="1" line2="145" col2="2" start="47851" end="47852">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="146" col1="1" line2="146" col2="28" start="48181" end="48208">#' @importFrom Biobase pData</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="147" col1="1" line2="147" col2="28" start="48511" end="48538">#' @importFrom Biobase fData</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="148" col1="1" line2="148" col2="28" start="48841" end="48868">#' @importFrom Biobase exprs</COMMENT>

  <COMMENT line1="541" col1="1" line2="541" col2="53" start="178531" end="178583">#' Identify if a cell is an outlier based on a metric</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="542" col1="1" line2="542" col2="3" start="178861" end="178863">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="543" col1="1" line2="543" col2="65" start="179191" end="179255">#' @param metric numeric or integer vector of values for a metric</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="544" col1="1" line2="544" col2="77" start="179521" end="179597">#' @param nmads scalar, number of median-absolute-deviations away from median</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="545" col1="1" line2="545" col2="47" start="179851" end="179897">#' required for a value to be called an outlier</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="546" col1="1" line2="546" col2="76" start="180181" end="180256">#' @param type character scalar, choice indicate whether outliers should be </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="547" col1="1" line2="547" col2="81" start="180511" end="180591">#' looked for at both tails (default: "both") or only at the lower end ("lower") </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="548" col1="1" line2="548" col2="31" start="180841" end="180871">#' or the higher end ("higher")</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="549" col1="1" line2="549" col2="77" start="181171" end="181247">#' @param log logical, should the values of the metric be transformed to the </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="550" col1="1" line2="550" col2="80" start="181501" end="181580">#' log10 scale before computing median-absolute-deviation for outlier detection?</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="551" col1="1" line2="551" col2="77" start="181831" end="181907">#' @param subset logical or integer vector, which subset of values should be </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="552" col1="1" line2="552" col2="73" start="182161" end="182233">#' used to calculate the median/MAD? If \code{NULL}, all values are used.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="553" col1="1" line2="553" col2="76" start="182491" end="182566">#' Missing values will trigger a warning and will be automatically ignored. </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="554" col1="1" line2="554" col2="77" start="182821" end="182897">#' @param batch factor of length equal to \code{metric}, specifying the batch</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="555" col1="1" line2="555" col2="80" start="183151" end="183230">#' to which each observation belongs. A median/MAD is calculated for each batch,</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="556" col1="1" line2="556" col2="54" start="183481" end="183534">#' and outliers are then identified within each batch.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="557" col1="1" line2="557" col2="3" start="183811" end="183813">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="558" col1="1" line2="558" col2="79" start="184141" end="184219">#' @description Convenience function to determine which values for a metric are</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="559" col1="1" line2="559" col2="53" start="184471" end="184523">#' outliers based on median-absolute-deviation (MAD).</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="560" col1="1" line2="560" col2="3" start="184801" end="184803">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="561" col1="1" line2="561" col2="76" start="185131" end="185206">#' @return a logical vector of the same length as the \code{metric} argument</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="562" col1="1" line2="562" col2="3" start="185461" end="185463">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="563" col1="1" line2="563" col2="10" start="185791" end="185800">#' @export</COMMENT>

  <COMMENT line1="648" col1="1" line2="648" col2="89" start="213841" end="213929">#' "tpm", "fpkm" and "exprs" (default), or anything else in the object added manually by </COMMENT>

  <COMMENT line1="1233" col1="1" line2="1233" col2="76" start="406891" end="406966">#' equal to \code{nrow(object)}. If \code{NULL}, then the function checks if</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1234" col1="1" line2="1234" col2="79" start="407221" end="407299">#' feature controls are defined. If so, then only feature controls are plotted,</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1235" col1="1" line2="1235" col2="41" start="407551" end="407591">#' if not, then all features are plotted.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1236" col1="1" line2="1236" col2="83" start="407881" end="407963">#' @param feature_controls character, numeric or logical vector indicating a set of</COMMENT>

                  <OP-RIGHT-PAREN line1="1473" col1="31" line2="1473" col2="31" start="486121" end="486121">)</OP-RIGHT-PAREN>
                </expr>
              </expr>

  <COMMENT line1="1480" col1="1" line2="1480" col2="80" start="488401" end="488480">################################################################################</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1482" col1="1" line2="1482" col2="44" start="489061" end="489104">#' Plot a relative log expression (RLE) plot</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1483" col1="1" line2="1483" col2="2" start="489391" end="489392">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1484" col1="1" line2="1484" col2="82" start="489721" end="489802">#' Produce a relative log expression (RLE) plot of one or more transformations of </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1485" col1="1" line2="1485" col2="26" start="490051" end="490076">#' cell expression values.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1486" col1="1" line2="1486" col2="2" start="490381" end="490382">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1487" col1="1" line2="1487" col2="40" start="490711" end="490750">#' @param object an \code{SCESet} object</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1488" col1="1" line2="1488" col2="80" start="491041" end="491120">#' @param exprs_mats named list of expression matrices. Entries can either be a </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1489" col1="1" line2="1489" col2="79" start="491371" end="491449">#' character string, in which case the corresponding expression matrix will be </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1490" col1="1" line2="1490" col2="77" start="491701" end="491777">#' extracted from the SCESet \code{object}, or a matrix of expression values.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1491" col1="1" line2="1491" col2="84" start="492031" end="492114">#' @param exprs_logged logical vector of same length as \code{exprs_mats} indicating</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1492" col1="1" line2="1492" col2="82" start="492361" end="492442">#' whether the corresponding entry in \code{exprs_mats} contains logged expression</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1493" col1="1" line2="1493" col2="46" start="492691" end="492736">#' values (\code{TRUE}) or not (\code{FALSE}).</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1494" col1="1" line2="1494" col2="83" start="493021" end="493103">#' @param colour_by character string defining the column of \code{pData(object)} to</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1495" col1="1" line2="1495" col2="81" start="493351" end="493431">#' be used as a factor by which to colour the points in the plot. Alternatively, </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1496" col1="1" line2="1496" col2="83" start="493681" end="493763">#' a data frame with one column, containing values to map to colours for all cells.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1497" col1="1" line2="1497" col2="81" start="494011" end="494091">#' @param style character(1), either \code{"minimal"} (default) or \code{"full"},</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1498" col1="1" line2="1498" col2="84" start="494341" end="494424">#' defining the boxplot style to use. \code{"minimal"} uses Tufte-style boxplots and</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1499" col1="1" line2="1499" col2="68" start="494671" end="494738">#' is fast for large numbers of cells. \code{"full"} uses the usual </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1500" col1="1" line2="1500" col2="80" start="495001" end="495080">#' \code{\link{ggplot2}} and is more detailed and flexible, but can take a long </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1501" col1="1" line2="1501" col2="35" start="495331" end="495365">#' time to plot for large datasets.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1502" col1="1" line2="1502" col2="77" start="495661" end="495737">#' @param legend character, specifying how the legend(s) be shown? Default is</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1503" col1="1" line2="1503" col2="80" start="495991" end="496070">#' \code{"auto"}, which hides legends that have only one level and shows others.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1504" col1="1" line2="1504" col2="44" start="496321" end="496364">#' Alternative is "none" (hide all legends).</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1505" col1="1" line2="1505" col2="76" start="496651" end="496726">#' @param order_by_colour logical, should cells be ordered (grouped) by the </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1506" col1="1" line2="1506" col2="77" start="496981" end="497057">#' \code{colour_by} variable? Default is \code{TRUE}. Useful for visualising </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1507" col1="1" line2="1507" col2="58" start="497311" end="497368">#' differences between batches or experimental conditions.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1508" col1="1" line2="1508" col2="73" start="497641" end="497713">#' @param ncol integer, number of columns for the facetting of the plot. </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1509" col1="1" line2="1509" col2="16" start="497971" end="497986">#' Default is 1.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1510" col1="1" line2="1510" col2="78" start="498301" end="498378">#' @param ... further arguments passed to \code{\link[ggplot2]{geom_boxplot}}.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1511" col1="1" line2="1511" col2="2" start="498631" end="498632">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1512" col1="1" line2="1512" col2="31" start="498961" end="498991">#' @return a ggplot plot object</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1513" col1="1" line2="1513" col2="2" start="499291" end="499292">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1514" col1="1" line2="1514" col2="12" start="499621" end="499632">#' @details </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1515" col1="1" line2="1515" col2="86" start="499951" end="500036">#' Unwanted variation can be highly problematic and so its detection is often crucial.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1516" col1="1" line2="1516" col2="80" start="500281" end="500360">#' Relative log expression (RLE) plots are a powerful tool for visualising such </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1517" col1="1" line2="1517" col2="76" start="500611" end="500686">#' variation in high dimensional data. RLE plots are particularly useful for</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1518" col1="1" line2="1518" col2="78" start="500941" end="501018">#' assessing whether a procedure aimed at removing unwanted variation, i.e. a </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1519" col1="1" line2="1519" col2="79" start="501271" end="501349">#' normalisation procedure, has been successful. These plots, while originally </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1520" col1="1" line2="1520" col2="81" start="501601" end="501681">#' devised for gene expression data from microarrays, can also be used to reveal </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1521" col1="1" line2="1521" col2="82" start="501931" end="502012">#' unwanted variation in single-cell expression data, where such variation can be </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1522" col1="1" line2="1522" col2="15" start="502261" end="502275">#' problematic.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1523" col1="1" line2="1523" col2="3" start="502591" end="502593">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1524" col1="1" line2="1524" col2="80" start="502921" end="503000">#' If style is "full", as usual with boxplots, the box shows the inter-quartile </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1525" col1="1" line2="1525" col2="80" start="503251" end="503330">#' range and whiskers extend no more than 1.5 * IQR from the hinge (the 25th or </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1526" col1="1" line2="1526" col2="82" start="503581" end="503662">#' 75th percentile). Data beyond the whiskers are called outliers and are plotted </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1527" col1="1" line2="1527" col2="72" start="503911" end="503982">#' individually. The median (50th percentile) is shown with a white bar.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1528" col1="1" line2="1528" col2="3" start="504241" end="504243">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1529" col1="1" line2="1529" col2="79" start="504571" end="504649">#' If style is "minimal", then median is shown with a circle, the IQR in a grey</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1530" col1="1" line2="1530" col2="81" start="504901" end="504981">#' line, and "whiskers" (as defined above) for the plots are shown with coloured </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1531" col1="1" line2="1531" col2="52" start="505231" end="505282">#' lines. No outliers are shown for this plot style.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1532" col1="1" line2="1532" col2="2" start="505561" end="505562">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1533" col1="1" line2="1533" col2="15" start="505891" end="505905">#' @references </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1534" col1="1" line2="1534" col2="94" start="506221" end="506314">#' Gandolfo LC, Speed TP. RLE Plots: Visualising Unwanted Variation in High Dimensional Data. </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="1535" col1="1" line2="1535" col2="68" start="506551" end="506618">#' arXiv [stat.ME]. 2017. Available: http://arxiv.org/abs/1704.03590</COMMENT>
